attributes.label: DS2 Unresponsive  Financial System (V1-)
attributes.description: This is the first of two Deep Structure loops. This loop is a combination of the loop Tilman identified and the one that Sarah drew. It would be paired with a second loop that is a generic/zoomed out loop that produces the rality/perception of household financial struggles (lack of financial health).

attributes.label: DS1 Increasing Household  Vulnerability (V2-)
attributes.description: The first of 2 Deep Structure loops, this vicious cycle is a basic dynamic that rests in increasing household financial vulnerability - this is a version of the loop that Tilman identified as the "perception and reality of socio-economic vulernability, and that is linked with the unresponsive financial system. This loop starts with less engagement with the traditional financial system means less income stability/sufficiency, means more household vulnerability, more reliance on low-quality products/the non-traditional financial system, resulting in greater feelings of exclusion (this was a relationship identified on the post-its we did in the deep structure exercise), which strengthens perceptions of self-perpetuating and inter-generational cycles of disadvantage (racism, gender inequality, etc.), which reduces trust in the traditional financial system, and further decreases engagement with the financial system.  My concern with these two loops is that the are both vicious, but there are other balancing and even virtuous loops that can plug in here - as well as the deeper dynamics Tilman called out around shrinking support systems (family and friends, societal pressures, and macro-economic forces.
